#OnTheGo

Jaguars take lead against Cobras, 56-46

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars dominated against the Southwestern University (SWU) PHINMA Cobras, 56-46, fending off the victory during their basketball match in Cesafi 23 at Cebu Coliseum yesterday, September 28.

From the opening tip-off, the Jaguars clearly had a game plan geared toward bagging the victory against the Cobras.

Their offense flowed seamlessly, with precise passes, sharp shoots, and a tenacious presence in the paint, which left the Cobras behind with an 8-point lead in the first quarter, 20-12.

Jaguars’ big man, Evan Jose Ejay Agbong, was in a league of his own, contributing game-high points and displaying an ability to control the tempo of the game.

Agbong shared his eagerness and preparation to win the competition.

“Hungrier pa [ako] kasi hindi naman ito ang pinaghahandaan ko na game eh, part lang ito sa process namin, pero ang pinaghahandaan namin is ang goal namin [to go] to the finals. Ang dami pang teams na haharapin namin at madami pang challenges na haharapin namin,” he explained.

As the game progressed, the Jaguars were not content with their initial lead and continued to execute fast breaks with precision and make paints that swamped their opponents, garnering a 21-point lead against the Cobras, by the end of the first half, 51-30.

Despite the Cobras’ efforts to mount a comeback in the fourth quarter, they were unable to overcome the Jaguars’ relentless onslaught, leaving a final score of 56-46.

Jaguars head coach Melo Banua, shared his sentiments about improving the team’s loophole.

“Mao gihapon ang amoang problema last game nga every time last four or three minutes, [mag]-collapse [ang offense and defense sa] mga bata, so kinahanglan pa jud nga i-build ang chemistry para sure nga modaog sa game," he shared.

The USJ-R Jaguars will face off against the Cebu Roosevelt Memorial Colleges (CRMC) Mustangs on Sunday, October 1, at 5 p.m.

via Khabzeel Clark Payao | FORWARD Probationary Writer

[LITERARY]

Our Enchanting Tale
by Kady De Arca | Josenian Contributor

In the abandoned corridors of my heart,
Your footsteps suddenly echo from within.
The massive walls I built were torn apart,
Showing an open door where roses bloomed, and so, it begins.

In the night filled with a sea of stars,
You were once the moon I couldn't ever reach.
The moon I could only admire and gaze from afar,
The moon I so badly love and desire.

Then the season of autumn arrived,
Just like the leaves, I was slowly falling.
Yet the breeze of your words blew me astray,
Along with your actions, which completely lost my way.

Winter came, and your footsteps slowly faded away,
Coldness replaced the warmth within my heart.
By surprise, you finally entered my doors inserting the key,
Thus an enchanting tale began; a tale that started with pure glee.

The first road in our story,
Was the first lesson of compromise and adaptability.
Then the truth of our love came to light,
Memorable it was, truth be told, the prank you pulled gave me quite a fright.

As months passed by,
The first grenade and proceeding bullets came.
It was hard and painful, not gonna lie,
Yet every tear that dropped was worth it, because we still fought and won every battle we faced.

Now we’ve reached the here and now,
But still the war is not yet done.
Though my heart is filled with more warmth than sorrow,
For I know you're with me in every battle, we'll win.

With that, I'll confess,
In the entirety of my heart, mind, body and soul,
Your voice is my guide, your laugh is my melody,
Your eyes are my dream, the beat of your heart is my harmony.

Your arms are my home,
Your scent is my remedy.
For that my roses are yours,
And yours it shall be for all of eternity.

Illustration by Karina Adel Vestil | FORWARD Staff Artist

Josenian Debatista champs USC’s Borderlands Cup

The Josenian Debatista (JD) from the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) clinched the championship title in the University of San Carlos Junior Philippine Institute of Accountants’ (USC JPIA) Borderlands Cup held on September 23-24.

USJ-R’s ‘Alice Outside of the Borderland’ team was composed of Jelene Gabutan, a fourth-year BS in Accountancy student, and Jan Kier Rizon, a third-year BS in Management Accounting student.

Rizon and Gabutan claimed the 1st and 2nd Best Speaker awards, respectively.

Rizon expressed his sentiments on winning and representing the University.

“It was a very proud moment for me to get the name of the school out there. Most especially representing our much-loved org, the Josenian Debatista,” he said.

“Our seniors really helped us train and improve as we moved along with our training sessions. Being named as champions representing the mighty banner of my alma mater that bleeds green and gold was a surreal moment,” he added.

Meanwhile, Gabutan shared the challenging experience during the competition.

“I think the hardest part about the competition was the fact that you have all these participants from different schools who also want to win so it can get quite intimidating at first,” she said.

Meanwhile, Jet Francis Camasura, a fourth-year BS in Accountancy student, earned the 3rd Best Speaker as part of the participating team.

Further, JD’s Athena Matin-aw, a third-year BA in International Studies student, served as an invited judge at the Borderlands Cup.

Matin-aw was also awarded the title of Best Adjudicator in the tournament.

“It was a nice surprise that they accepted my application to be an invited adjudicator, as admittedly I’m more experienced in debating rather than judging. But really, the award was unexpected, and I’m very grateful to the organizers (USC JPIA Debate Society) and the Adjudication Core for letting me join the tournament,” Matin-aw said.

The Borderlands Cup hosted by USC JPIA Debate Society, is a platform for novice JPIA debaters to showcase their talents and hone their skills.

It provides a competitive arena for young debaters to engage in intellectual discourse and develop their abilities in persuasive argumentation.

The Borderlands Cup Grand Finals was held online through Discord and was broadcast live at the USC JPIA Debate Society Facebook Page.

via Maria Cristina Lamug | FORWARD Probationary Writer

#OnTheGo

Jaguars emerge victorious against Warriors in Cesafi basketball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars claimed their first victory in a close game, 60-58, against the University of San Carlos (USC) Warriors during their first basketball match in Cesafi 23 at Cebu Coliseum yesterday, September 24.

The USJ-R Jaguars trailed behind the USC Warriors with a 4-point lead in the first 2 minutes of the game but eventually caught up and maintained their domination.

In the final period, the Jaguars sustained their momentum and strategized their defense against the Warriors, earning an advantage of more than 10 points.

The tension of the game heated up as the Warriors almost secured their first win when they took the game to a tie, 58-58, in the dying seconds of the last quarter.

The Jaguars’ utmost focus to augment the lead and the Warriors’ eagerness to earn the win via a 3-point shot filled the crowd with excitement.

The team finally sealed the game with a winning 2-point shot secured by Kendrick Abarquez.

USJ-R Jaguars Head Coach Melo Banua expressed his sentiments about the game.

“Gwapo kaayo ang duwa wala [nako’y] maingon sa duwa. Nahurot na akong boses so ang good thing lang ari is wala ni-give up akong mga players,” he said.

Meanwhile, the Jaguars’ team captain Jules Langres shared that he could not explain what they were feeling at the drop of a hat.

“Nagpasalamat lang ko kay God kay gitagaan mi niya’g nindot na duwa. Amo ning gi-offer sa among coach. Composed lang mi kay gianad man mi. Di pa nako ma-explain tanan kay mixed [akong] emotion ba,” Langres stated.

The USJ-R Jaguars will face off against the Southwestern University (SWU) PHINMA Cobras on September 28 at 6:45 p.m.

#OnTheGo

Aspiring lawyers complete final day of 2023 Bar Exams

The aspiring lawyers concluded their three-day journey toward legal licensure as the regionalized 2023 Bar Examinations unfolded at various venues, including one at the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Basak campus, yesterday, September 24.

Ellen Lois Badon, a Bar examinee from USJ-R, shared her sentiments now that the three-day examinations are finally over.

“I feel happy that after five years nga hinaguan karon kay nahuman na gyud akong gihulat: ang Bar Exam. Dako kaayo og tabang ang mga professors, ang mga Bar officials, and ang USJ-R sa paghatag sa amoa sa ilang support. Makita sad gyud ang support sa mga tawo nga naa diri karon,” Badon said.

Badon further shared her thoughts with regards to the traffic management system as there were no road closures implemented at the USJ-R Basak campus in Basak Pardo.

“Nalipay pod ko nga sa USJ-R na-held ang regionalized Bar Exam, pero medyo layo sad gyud siya unya traffic,” Badon said.

“Siguro akong ma-suggest sa Bar Officers kay mayta’g mohatag sila og free ride sa examinees kay lisod kaayo ang biyahe,” Badon added.

Meanwhile, Gracezyl Blanco, a Bar examinee from Cagayan De Oro, also expressed her experience of the regionalized Bar Exam being held in Cebu.

“Although dinhi man ko sa Cebu nag-eskwela before, first time nako nakasulod sa USJ-R Basak. Nindot siya and daghan og facilities pero traffic gyud siya inig pauli. Pero usually sayo man pod mi sa buntag so okay ra siya,” she said.

As aspiring lawyers, Badon and Blanco held high hopes for all examinees.

“Kung ihatag sa Ginoo na mahimo ming abogado, unta dili makalimtan ang reason ngano ni-choose mi mahimong lawyer: To bring justice to those that are in need,” Badon concluded.

Moreover, Zoilo Yu, a Basak Pardo Barangay Public Safety Officer (BPSO), conveyed his experiences while working onsite.

“Malipay mi nga respetohon mi sa among mga gibadlong kay makita namo na wala ray aberya sa pag-take sa mga examinees. Kalipay pod namo na makita ang ilang pagdasig ug ang pagkawala sa ilang kakapoy gikan sa pag-take kada naay mo-congratulate nila,” Yu said.

The Supreme Court chose two private universities in Cebu City which served as local testing centers (LTC) for the 2023 Bar Examinations, namely USJ-R and University of San Carlos (USC).

This marks the second time that USJ-R has served as a venue for the regionalized Bar Examinations.

#OnTheGo

USJ-R bets remain hopeful despite defeat

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) representatives remain optimistic despite their setback during the Miss Cebu Schools Athletics Foundation Incorporated (Cesafi) Season 23 held at the Cebu Coliseum yesterday, September 23.

In both the College and High School divisions, Heart Heather Burden and Kristen Dawn Delerio respectively, did not secure any awards.

Nevertheless, Burden expressed her gratitude for the opportunity to represent the University on a big stage.

“Although wala nadaog, happy gihapon ko ron knowing that gipili ko sa USJ-R to represent our school and this has been such a valuable experience now that I can learn something that can help me grow,” she stated.

Burden also shared that she advocates for climate change and had plans to further collaborate with the government and community to take action for practical solutions.

Meanwhile, Sophia Verron, a first-year USJ-R student and attendee of the Miss Cesafi coronation, shared her sentiments about the results.

“USJ-R this Cesafi may have not won but kami nga Josenians are still very proud of how they carried the school and [themselves,]” Verron said.

Here is the official list of winners of Miss Cesafi 2023:

College Division

Miss Cesafi - Leila Alexis Mah (USPF)
1st runner-up - Jannah Salazar, University of the Philippines-Cebu (UPC)
2nd runner-up - Leigh Chanelle Ong, Cebu Doctors’ University (CDU)

Special Awards (College Division)

Miss SMART Cesafi - Leigh Chanelle Ong (CDU)
Miss Photogenic - Reina Alexis Bentigue, Southwestern University (SWU) PHINMA

High School Division

Miss Cesafi - Camille Frances Maamo, Sacred Heart School Ateneo de Cebu (SHS-AdC)
1st runner-up - Bvhlgryl Chelsea Barinan (USPF)
2nd runner-up - Arabella Ynez Marundan Salgado (CDU)

Special Awards (High School Division)

Miss SMART Cesafi - Camille Frances Maamo (SHS AdC)
Miss Photogenic - Charmelle Lawi-An, University of Cebu (UC)

Last year during Cesafi 2022, USJ-R managed to clinch the 2nd place in the High School division and Miss Photogenic title in the College division.

#OnTheGo

Josenian alumni hailed as Mr. & Ms. Press Freedom 2023

Cebu Daily News (CDN) Digital’s Christian Gerard Jamora and SunStar Cebu’s Jewil Anne Tabiolo, who both graduated from the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R), bagged the Mr. and Ms. Press Freedom 2023 title at the Axis Bar, NUSTAR Resort and Casino on September 21.

Tabiolo, a BA Journalism alumna batch 2022, relished the exclusivity and challenges of the event as it was her first time showcasing her beauty and intellect on stage.

“This event held immense personal significance as it allowed me to fulfill a lifelong ambition. An ambition of the young girl within me. Winning the crown felt like a journey of self-discovery in the most beautiful way possible," she said.

As the reigning Miss Press Freedom, Tabiolo pledged to connect with aspiring journalists, particularly within the USJ-R community.

”Our alma mater has consistently produced outstanding journalists working across various media outlets, and I’m proud to be part of that legacy and to become the new face of Cebu media,” she said.

”I believe it’s crucial to launch [a] public awareness campaign about the vital role of the press and challenge the misconceptions that portray journalists as societal villains. It’s never wrong to demand accountability and transparency from those in power,” she added.

Meanwhile, Jamora, a BA Communication alumnus batch 2022, had previous experience in pageantry during high school at Colegio De La Medalla Milagrosa, securing the Mr. Intramurals 2016 title.

“I never expected to be part of an event like this again considering that it’s one of the biggest events in Cebu. Because pageantry was never my forte nor a passion to begin with. Nevertheless, I still accepted the challenge because I look at Mr. and Ms. Press Freedom as a tool to represent the empowerment of the media,”he said.

Jamora expressed pride in representing his alma mater outside its walls and urged Josenians to uphold the institution’s core values.

“Uplift and empower the media as an institution that promotes responsibility in the fourth estate by informing the news and purveying the truth in the right way,” he said.

Furthermore, Jessa Ngojo, a social media specialist at CDN and a USJ-R graduate of BA Journalism, also secured the first runner-up spot.

via Sharry Cuizon | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Niña Mae Oliverio | CDN Digital

#OnTheGo

USJ-R CRCESI conducts reading assessments for children in Carbon

The University of San Jose-Recoletos Center for Recollect Community Engagement and Social Involvement (USJ-R CRCESI) held a program for children in Carbon to improve their reading comprehension, at the USJ-R Main Lobby earlier today, September 23.

CRCESI Project Facilitator for Outreach Activities, Jose Peace Fuentes, explained that “Paglaum sa mga Bata sa Carbon” is spearheaded to evaluate the children ages 4-15 years old in their ability to understand passages.

“I-evaluate ang ilang reading comprehension kay bisan [pila] pa ang ilang mga age, dili man mo matter sa comprehension,” Fuentes said.

The facilitator then categorized the children on how extensive their learning process would be through four categories: Non-reader, Developing, Intermediate, and Proficient.

Fuentes added that this process will not only instill knowledge, but would also help the children in the long run.

Meanwhile, Charlene Guiral, one of the volunteer teachers from the Elementary Department, shared that she finds this initiative ”helpful” because it recognizes the pressing need for improving literacy in the community.

”So far murag okay ra ang mga bata pero naa juy uban nga dili pa siya nagpantay like nine years old na sila pero ilahang grade level kay naa pa sa Grade 2 [or] Grade 1. I encountered one, kamao man siya mobasa pero mga one syllable to two syllables pa lang,” she added.

In addition, CRCESI also started to disseminate the children’s IDs for their next programs that will be held in the future.

via John Louise Lambiquit | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Narvie Klaryzze Borja | FORWARD Probationary Photographer

#OnTheGo

CDN Digital promotes responsible journalism in 31st Press Freedom Week

Media professionals from Cebu Daily News (CDN) Digital, along with journalism and communication students from various universities in Cebu, wrapped up the 31st Press Freedom Week with a forum on responsible journalism in the digital era at the University of the Philippines - Cebu (UPC) Arts and Sciences Hall on September 22.

The speakers at the forum were CDN Digital’s Content Creator Immae Lachica, Senior Copy Editor Brian Ochoa, and Social Media Manager Ralph Gurango.

In Lachica’s discussion titled “Social Media, Journalism, and the Space Between,” she emphasized the importance of news verification, particularly in the digital space.

“Not everything you see online is true, that is why you need to verify,” Lachica said.

Lachica also mentioned that journalistic ethics must still be applied in digital journalism.

“You have to be sensitive in dealing with the sources, in dealing with a tragedy, especially kay dili nana nimo ma-retract everything you post online,” she added.

Meanwhile, Ochoa highlighted that there is little to no difference between traditional and digital media in terms of journalism practices, but the digital space places a greater emphasis on delivering news in real-time.

“That is the name of the game in digital [journalism]—speed,” Ochoa said.

However, he added, “At the end of the day, you just have to choose accuracy,” noting that while digital journalism is fast-paced, accuracy remains vital.

Further, Gurango shared how newsrooms have changed in the digital landscape.

“The nature of the platform demands that you provide news as [accurately] and as fast as possible,” Gurango said.

Gurango then posed the challenge to future journalists to “constantly try to understand the tools that are available to us.”

“Being a great journalist still matters but evolving with the digital space also matters. In fact, knowing who your audience is, matters,” he added.

Moreover, Atty. Archill Niña Pistrano, assistant professor & coordinator of UPC’s Office of Anti-Sexual Harassment (OASH), emphasized in her opening speech how responsible communication is important in a democratic society.

“The media, your profession, enriches and empowers a democracy, especially in the digital age, when disinformation has become the order of the day. It is important for the young generation, the next generation, to therefore be empowered to be responsible communicators,” she said.

The students in attendance at the forum were from UPC, University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R), Cebu Normal University (CNU), and Cebu Technological University (CTU).

via Rey Martin Rio | FORWARD Staff Writer

Photos Courtesy: Christian Mananguite & Astrid Niña Vidal | FORWARD Staff Photographers

#OnTheGo

91 Josenians complete LECPA 2023

A total of 91 Josenian examinees completed the third and last day of the Licensure Examination for Certified Public Accountants (LECPA) at the Abellana National School (ANS) on Monday afternoon, October 2.

Josenian examinee, Erik Mendiola, described his last day of the CPA examination as a “tiring yet fulfilling goal of his life.”

“Taking the exam was a leap of faith bitaw…It was hard of course, mao na jud na s’ya but it is fulfilling, very fulfilling,” he said.

Mendiola mentioned that despite doubts and worries, prayers greatly aided him during the exams.

He added that taking and passing the exam were among his main goals for this year, and he eagerly looks forward to seeing the results.

Meanwhile, another Josenian examinee, Joyce Sabelgas, admitted that the exam for the third day was difficult compared to the first and second examinations.

“Before ko nigawas sa gate, nihapit sad ko sa chapel kay lisod jud ang exam, nga despite sa nahitabo sa exam ma-okay ra jud ang tanan,” Sabelgas said.

Sabelgas also shared that seeing the cheers of her fellow examinees left her in tears and she can finally say she made it until the end.

Aside from the exam takers, the members of the Professional Review Training Center (PRTC) and fellow Josenians from the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) continued to cheer at the gates of ANS.

Kristine June Uy, the CPA Review Director of USJ-R, shared her happiness and pride in the CPA takers for successfully completing the three-day examination.

“It wasn’t easy, but seeing them come out of it with smiles is something I am most grateful for,” she said.

Uy also expressed her gratitude for the unwavering support provided to the Josenian examinees throughout the review and exam period.

Meanwhile, four other Josenian examinees took the exams at other testing centers in the Philippines.

via Aliyaah Alvez | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Photos Courtesy: Marylit Silje Cañizar | FORWARD Probationary Photographer

text:
[JOSENIANS MOVING FORWARD]

Strokes of Resilience: Palette of Perseverance
by Khabzeel Clark Payao | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Despite the mountainous path that lies ahead, to achieve our dream, it is essential to step outside of our comfort zone, which can lead us closer to paradise.

Take inspiration from Daniella Kristine Lerio, a third-year Bachelor of Arts in English Language Studies student and a self-taught artist currently based in Cebu.

Lerio’s deep affection for art began when she was four years old, when she started to aspire to become an artist someday.

In an interview with FORWARD, Lerio shared her sentiments on the journey to achieve her paradise, witnessing the beauty of her hard work and perseverance.

“To achieve that dream, I pushed myself to explore outside of my comfort zone. So, I decided to join national and international art competitions where I gained recognition for my works,” she said.

Stepping outside of her comfort zone brought her closer to achieving her goal by participating in national events such as the 9th Manila Bulletin Sketchfest under the On-the-Spot category with the theme, “Fiestas & Colors of the Philippines,” and the 2020 Sergio “Serging” Osmeña Jr. Oil Painting Contest.

Despite not making it to the finals, she remains grateful for the opportunity to participate in these events as they helped her flourish her skills and learn more about art styles.

These setbacks didn’t deter Lerio from pursuing her passion for traditional art; instead, she strived for mastery by joining international competitions and garnering numerous awards and recognitions.

Lerio was awarded the ASEAN Prize Award at the 2021 4th ASEAN Culture House Design Contest organized by the Korea Foundation and the ASEAN Culture House for her artwork “Timeless Until Tomorrow” in the Illustration category. She also received an Honourable Mention Award for her artwork “Chained Wings” in the 16-18 category at the 24th ShinHan Postcard Art Contest hosted by ShinHan Art Materials.

Recently, she participated in Australia’s Small Scale Art Prize, the Lethbridge 20000, where she created a still-life painting of chess pieces called “d4” and was featured as a finalist in the gallery’s online exhibition.

“As a gallery finalist, I’m thankful to be part of such a prestigious event where I could share my painting alongside other talented artists. It was also a meaningful opportunity to share my artwork, ‘d4,’ which holds a special place in my heart. It was inspired by my poem, also entitled ’d4,’ and serves as a poetic representation of the chess opening, Queen’s Gambit,” she explained.

Despite the colorful and challenging path she boldly overcame, Lerio recalled her unforgettable moment when she opened the door and ventured outside of her comfort zone, shaping her into the artist she is today.

“My most memorable art competition was the Graines d’artistes du monde entier - Concours international d’arts plastiques 2019 (2019 International Visual Arts Competition) organized by UNESCO Center Louis François in Troyes, France. It was my first art competition that enabled me to learn and discover new techniques and art skills, as well as use my creativity to encourage others to see the value of art. With this experience, I was inspired to explore further and eventually came up with the idea of incorporating poetry into my paintings,” she shared.

Painting also serves as Lerio’s gateway to soothing her pain and negativity, especially amidst the pandemic, allowing her to find solace and healing in the strokes of colors and creativity.

In the vibrant canvas of her life, Lerio is a muse for young people, using her palette of perseverance, determination, and a positive mindset to break through the barriers of fear and step outside of our comfort zones. This, she believes, will lead us closer to our desired portrait of paradise if we resist the urge to give up.

“Always make time for the things you love, be it in the visual arts, sports, writing, music, dance, public speaking, or any field where you excel. You should always make time to do the things you are passionate about because it is when you try that you will discover your potential. If you’re afraid to take the step because no one has done it before, then be the first to do it because your talent is unique,” she said.

Lerio wants to remind the youth to never abandon their goals in life amidst difficulties and multiple failures and to take one step at a time. This adds shades of hope and resilience, turning our challenges into magnificent works of art.

Visuals by Hannah Vanessa Mondilla | FORWARD Staff Artist & Narvie Klaryzze Borja | FORWARD Probationary Artist

With this experience, I was inspired to explore further and eventually came up with the idea of incorporating poetry into my paintings,” she shared.

Painting also serves as Lerio’s gateway to soothing her pain and negativity, especially amidst the pandemic, allowing her to find solace and healing in the strokes of colors and creativity.

In the vibrant canvas of her life, Lerio is a muse for young people, using her palette of perseverance, determination, and a positive mindset to break through the barriers of fear and step outside of our comfort zones. This, she believes, will lead us closer to our desired portrait of paradise if we resist the urge to give up.

“Always make time for the things you love, be it in the visual arts, sports, writing, music, dance, public speaking, or any field where you excel. You should always make time to do the things you are passionate about because it is when you try that you will discover your potential. If you’re afraid to take the step because no one has done it before, then be the first to do it because your talent is unique,” she said.

Lerio wants to remind the youth to never abandon their goals in life amidst difficulties and multiple failures and to take one step at a time. This adds shades of hope and resilience, turning our challenges into magnificent works of art.

#OnTheGo

Jaguars gain third win in offense-defense play against newcomer Mustangs

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars displayed resilience on the court and secured their third consecutive basketball victory after defeating the Cesafi 23 rookie Cebu Roosevelt Memorial Colleges (CRMC) Mustangs, 77-57, on Sunday, October 1, at the Cebu Coliseum.

The USJ-R Jaguars didn’t have the ideal start as they missed out on the first tip-off, allowing the CRMC Mustangs to surge ahead during the first quarter of the game.

However, amidst the adversity, the first quarter ended on a high note for USJ-R, thanks to the heroics of Jaguars’ team captain Jules Langres, who also nailed a buzzer-beating shot, ending the score at 21-15.

The momentum continued to swing in the Jaguars’ favor throughout the second quarter, with the team extending their lead to 37-25 by halftime.

The Jaguars’ head coach Melo Banua acknowledged the turbulent start but remained confident in the team’s abilities.

“Noong first half, medyo gubot. Wala kaayo’y na-execute [sa plan]. Pag-second half, adto na-execute ang usual play, game plan, and depensa sa mga players,” he said.

The second half of the game witnessed a remarkable resurgence from the Jaguars.

The team’s shooting prowess was on full display as they unleashed a barrage of three-pointers, leaving the Mustangs struggling to catch up.

Banua also commended his players, emphasizing that each one of them was a star of the game.

Meanwhile, the team’s shooting guard and small forward Elmer Echavez Jr. expressed his surprise at being singled out by Banua.

“Wala ko nag-expect, kay pag-first half, na-foul trouble ko. Unya pag-second half, mao to, akong gi-sud sa akong huna-huna nga dapat naa koy ma-ambag sa team, labi na nga senior player ko,” Echavez said.

With the Jaguars’ victory under their belts, the team looks ahead to their next challenge as they face the University of the Philippines-Cebu (UPC) Fighting Maroons on Sunday, October 8, at 5 p.m. and at the same venue.

#OnTheGo

Josenian CPA aspirants take LECPA exam

Josenians hoping to attain the Certified Public Accountant (CPA) title completed the first day of the Licensure Examinations for Certified Public Accountants (LECPA) on Saturday morning, September 30.

A total of 91 examinees from the University of San Jose-Recoletos CPA Review Center (USJ-R CPAR) gathered at the Abellana National School (ANS) to take the exams.

ANS is the sole LECPA testing site in Cebu.

Meanwhile, four Josenian examinees took the exams at other examination sites across the country.

A Josenian examinee, Joy Sabelgas, shared how crucial it is to give oneself time to relax and rest in preparation for the exams.

“Nagtuon ko, but [yes], ako jung gitagaan akong self og saktong tug ug saktong kaon para balance,” Sabelgas said.

She added that she looks forward to passing the exam in just one take and to finally see the result of her preparations.

Outside the gates of ANS are friends and families of examinees showing their support to the LECPA takers.

Among them was CPA and Josenian alumna, Catherine Oclarit, who accompanied her daughter to the venue.

Oclarit shared her prayers as she witnessed the struggles and sleepless nights her own daughter went through in preparing for the examinations.

“I hope and pray nga molampos jud sila [ug] makab-ot nila ang ilahang mga damgo. Yes, looking forward na ma-CPA pod akong anak like me puhon-puhon, mag-ampo jud ko ana kanunay," she expressed.

Oclarit also shared her experiences during her time and can see herself reflected on her daughter.

“Ako jud siyang ingnon, ‘Salig lang kanunay sa Ginoo,’ [para] less ang worries. Dili lang jud maguol,” she said.

Her daughter is a LECPA first-time taker who also graduated from USJ-R.

Aside from Josenian LECPA takers, examinees who reside outside Cebu also took the exams in ANS.

Charlotte Arsaga, a thrice-taker of the LECPA exam from Palawan, proudly stated that her failures made her more persevering to try again and never let these downfalls define her.

“‘Yong hirap andun na, ‘yong failure nararanasan na rin pero yung failure hindi [siya] kasi dapat hindrance ng pag-abot ng pangarap mo,” Arsaga said.

She also mentioned how her experience honed her to pursue what she wanted and never back down amidst the challenges she went through.

The LECPA examinations are intended for graduates of the Bachelor of Science in Accountancy degree program from dates September 30, 2023, to October 2, 2023.

#OnTheGo

Josenians showcase talent, creativity in Dance Battle 2023

Josenians enrolled in the Physical Activity Towards Health and Fitness (PATHFit) course performed conceptual dance presentations for the much-anticipated PATHFit Week Dance Battle 2023 at the University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Basak Coliseum on Thursday afternoon, November 9.

Nine classes enrolled in PATHFit 3 Menu of Dance took part in the event under the guidance of PATHFit instructors Ms. Shaina Tolentin and Ms. Louanna Castañares.

The students executed different dance styles they mastered throughout the semester, all cladded with thematic costumes, as they jive and bop on this year’s theme, “Dances Through the Decades.”

Meanwhile, the fifth entry from the Monday 9:30–11:30 a.m. class clinched the champion title with their “Fitness Club” concept, aiming to inspire exercise through dance.

One of the dancers and a Bachelor of Science in Accountancy student, Marey Denise Capuno, shared her experience behind their winning production.

“Lingaw nga kapoy...We had fun together as a class,” she said.

She also mentioned that the activity served as a way for students to hone their “creative minds” and “unity” as a class.

“Nagtinabangay mi tanan ug collaborate sa concept. Over the break, we made sacrifices na mo-take og time para sa success and synchronization sa among dance,” she added.

The USJ-R PE Department organized the PATHFit Week Celebration.

From Zamboanga, with Love
by Louella Grace Eroma | Josenian Contributor

“Angel Grace, what do you want to be when you grow up?” I asked my sister while sitting in the chair in our garden.

“I want to be an architect one day, Kuya Aldee, and build a house for our parents,” she replied with a huge smile on her face.

My sister loves to draw buildings and houses, and she loves math too.

“What about you, Kuya Aldee, what is your dream?” she asked me.

“I want to become a lawyer one day and help the people who need legal advice and other legal assistance. And aside from that, I want to be the mayor of Zamboanga City,” I replied, smiling back at her.

“Wow, that‘s great, Kuya. It’s a long way to becoming the mayor of our city, especially since there are a lot of people fighting for that position. I hope and pray to God and Our Lady of the Pillar for you,” she said.

Yes, we are devotees of Our Lady of the Pillar, our patroness here in Zamboanga City.

Our mother called us for dinner and her voice could be heard outside.

“You go ahead, Angel Grace. I need to clean up the mess first,” I said to her before leaving.

Sometimes, being the eldest in the family is not easy. There are many responsibilities that you need to take care of, which can be tiring at times.

I went inside our house after cleaning and they were still eating. I sat down in a chair and got my food.

lAldee, Angel told me that you want to be mayor of Zamboanga City soon,” my mother said.

“Yes, Mama, I want to follow in my father’s footsteps,” I replied.

“Are you sure, Aldee? Being the mayor of Zamboanga City is not easy. You will deal with lots of paperwork, sign documents, and face the crowd,” my father said.

“But if that’s what you want, then I will support you,” Papa added.

“Muchísimas gracias (thank you), Papa,” I said and hugged him.

“Study well, Aldee,” he replied.

I have chosen to pursue a Bachelor of Arts in Political Science in college. This is the best degree program for me because I want to become a lawyer and study in Cebu City.

I decided to keep my decision to study in Cebu City a secret from my parents until after my graduation.

I know that it will be difficult to study in a city where I don’t speak its language, Cebuano. Our mother tongue here in Zamboanga City is Chavacano, a Spanish-based creole. This is why our city is also known as “Asia's Latin City.”

Dinner was over, and it was Angel Grace’s turn to wash the dishes while I prepared my things for school the next day to attend our graduation orientation.

While scrolling through my mother’s phone, I saw some announcements from our school and found out that I was the class valedictorian! I was surprised and delighted.

”Mom, Dad, look!” I exclaimed.

“Wow, Aldee, congratulations! You made it. We’re so proud of you,” my mother said. They were very happy with the news.

The next day, my mother woke me up and reminded me about the orientation.

I went straight to the bathroom while my mother cooked breakfast for me.

After taking a shower, I went to my bedroom to put on my uniform and eat my breakfast.

“Hurry up, Aldee! Your dad is waiting for you in the car!” my mom shouted from downstairs.

I was brushing my teeth at the time and in a hurry as well. I grabbed some of my things and went to the car.

As I made my way to school, I was met with a sea of students, all rushing to get to class. The crowd was so thick that I was nearly late. Luckily, I arrived safely after five minutes.

While walking to my classroom, I almost fell down the stairs.

Visayas Art Fair 2023, Bodega Caravan holds a press conference

The Visayas Art Fair (VAF) and Bodega Caravan’s four-day event commenced with a press conference at Horizons Cafe, Oakridge Business Park, on Thursday, November 9.

The Chairwoman of Cebu Design Week (CDW), Maria Luisa Booth, shared the core themes of art, culture, and design.

”In the past five years, we have opened art fairs, celebrating culture, promoting design, as we had trained shows, designed awards, and collaborated with the three segments: art, design, and culture communities of Cebu,” she said.

Booth also shared her team’s vision of renewing their brand through signature events that are soon to be announced on social media and web platforms.

Following Booth’s remarks, Laurie Boquiren, Chairwoman of VAF, announced the event will have 14 exhibitors from the Visayas, 12 from the National Capital Region (NCR), one from Mindanao, and two international participants from Korea.

“From the very first time, the Luzon Art Fair, the Visayas Art Fair, [and] Mindanao Art Fair—all of these three major art events will converge here in Cebu for the Visayas Art Fair,” she said.

Boquiren added that the three major art fairs are recognized by the National Commission for Culture and Arts (NCCA).

Moreover, the VAF is set to feature art installations along with the illumination event of a 25-foot crotched Christmas tree.

The President of CDW, Christina Gaston, explained that the inspiration for Bodega Caravan stems from the nostalgic allure of traditional traveling wood carts.

”From traditional traveling wood carts that would come to the cities from the province to show and sell to us that’s really where we got the name ‘Bodega Caravan,’” Gaston stated.

The last speaker for the conference, Gil Zaire ‘Butch’ Carungay, the Design Director and Cebu UNESCO City of Design Commissioner, Cebu City Tourism Commission, introduced the Blue Mangoes Award (BMA) as a platform to recognize and reward creativity across various disciplines.

”Entries are currently being accepted from designers and creative entrepreneurs not just in Cebu, but also within Region VI, VII, and VIII,” Carungay said.

Furthermore, Kenneth Cobonpue, a multi-awarded Filipino furniture designer and the Curator of Bodega Design Caravan, will be the speaker for VAF.

The VAF and Bodega Caravan will start on November 23 exclusively for VIPs, while the Bodega Caravan’s sales will begin on November 25.

The event will be open to the general public from 10 a.m. to 10 p.m. on November 24–26 at Oakridge Business Park.

New CPAs round up in testimonial dinner

The recent passers in the September-October 2023 Licensure Examination for Certified Public Accountants (LECPA) from the University of San Jose-Recoletos’ (USJ-R) Certified Public Accountants (CPA) Review Center gathered for a testimonial dinner held at the Casino Español de Cebu on Wednesday, November 8.

The evening was filled with engaging activities, including the CPA Bingo, a creative spin on the classic game. Instead of numbers, they had to achieve various tasks all centered and related to their CPA journey.

One of the newly admitted CPAs and Josenian alumna, Maria Stella Cabague, emphasized the benefit of having a good support system throughout her academic journey.

“Very important gyod ang support system para nako. Despite sa kalisod sa program, sa kadaghang struggles nga na-experience namo, it was all bearable because we were all together,” she said.

“Every year, we always go somewhere, manglaag mi, mag-recharge mi, para the next year, mas stronger nami. Despite sa kalisod, naa gihapon mi’y something to look forward [to],” she added.

Jaguars falter against Webmasters, 59-73

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars fell short against the University of Cebu (UC) Webmasters, 59-73, in the Cesafi 23 Men's Basketball game on Tuesday evening, November 7, at the Cebu Coliseum.

The USJ-R Jaguars absorbed their second loss in seven games as they now sit at the third spot this season, behind the defending champions, the University of the Visayas (UV) Green Lancers (6-0), while the Webmasters are still undefeated (8-0).

Anchoring on the offense of their team captain Justine Langres, along with Klein Gordillo, and Elmer Echavez, had an excellent start as they capped off the opening period with a five-point lead (20-15) and stretched it to leave the Webmasters with eight points (34-26) by halftime.

However, the Jaguars turned cold at the start of the second half as some had foul troubles, which made a loophole in the team’s performance.

Their collapsed offense and defense in the third quarter also created a turning point in the match, allowing the Webmasters to eventually reduce the gap.

“Weakness sa team karon [kay] daghan kaayo'g turnovers, 'nya ang pinakadako sad nga problema is wala'y leadership ang point guards instead nga sila ang mag-coach sa sulod [sa court] nya mataranta na. Dako kaayo'g impact ba and at least kana ma-practice na,” Banua said.

The Webmasters took advantage of this dilemma and erased the Jaguars' advantage to one point, 42-41, before completely taking over the third period.

The opposing squad then went on to build a 13-point lead, 57-44, heading into the final period.

Meanwhile, one of the Jaguars' reliable guards, Karl Ventura, suffered an injury when he dislocated his right index finger during the third period as he attempted to poke the ball from the hands of UC's Ricofer Sordilla.

Despite the Jaguars’ effort in the fourth period through Echavez, Langres, and Karl Cabulao, managing to cut the lead at 56-65, the Webmasters quickly responded with an 8-1 run to seal their victory.

Echavez scored a total of 13 points, while Gordillo added 10 in their losing efforts.

Jaguars' Coach Melo Banua also shared that they will still “fight” and “prepare” for the next game and if the team wants to win, they should step up.

“Dili gihapon mi mo-give up, dako gihapon og chance ang team nga makasulod sa top 4. Also, [with] the team chemistry sa point guard and skills sa mga bata, kay daghan [pa] kaayo ta'g malabay na bola,” he said.

The Jaguars will have a chance at redemption as they take on the Benedicto College (BC) Cheetahs on November 12 at the same venue.

#OnTheGo

Lady Jaguars earn first win in Cesafi 23 Women’s Vball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Lady Jaguars swept the Cebu Institute of Technology-University (CIT-U) Wildcats, 3-0, in their first Cesafi 23 Women’s Volleyball match at the University of Southern Philippines Foundation (USPF) Gymnasium on Sunday, November 5.

The Lady Jaguars won their three-set campaign against the Wildcats by scoring 25-18, 18-25, 25-21.

Cesafi 22 Women’s Volleyball’s Most Valuable Player (MVP) Lounette Marie Abangan grabbed the first point for the Lady Jaguars with her overwhelming spike to the opposing team and continued their momentum to end the first set at 25-18.

The air moved in another direction in the middle of the second set for the Jaguars with their faulty attacks. However, the team capitalized on Alyssa Emboy’s spikes, pouncing on the Wildcats and furthered their win, 25-18.

The Wildcats began the third set with a booming point and rallied to equalize the game with the Jaguars, both exhibiting quick receives and strong net defense, but the Jaguars triumphantly clinched the third set with a score of 25-21.

Meanwhile, Abangan shared that her team needed to exert more effort in the game for their opponent was not a team to be complacent about.

“Nagka-bagat mi last year, di jud sila sayon nga kontra, sa among expectation. Laban ra gihapon mi, ug dili namo i-underestimate ang among kontra,” Abangan said.

Abangan added that they were anxious as it was their first game of the season, along with the addition of their new players.

“First ever game man gud ni namo sa season, so dili gihapon mawala ang kulba kay daghan pud og napuno sa team. Do what we can lang sa pagka-karon, labi na kay first game pa,” she said.

She further wished the team to be focused on defending their Cesafi championship title.

Moreover, Jaguars’ Head Coach Roldan Potot has one reminder for the team in this year’s women’s volleyball games.

“I always remind the girls nga dili makumpyansa kay lisod ang ikatulo. Nag-back-to-back mi last year. Hopefully, mao na amo gi-target ron nga makuha ang ikatulo. One game at a time,” Potot said.

The Lady Jaguars will battle against the University of Cebu (UC) Webmasters on November 12 at the same venue.

Crossword of Choices: The Growth of an Indomitable Spirit
by Louise Lambiquit | FORWARD Probationary Writer

Time-walking on a seemingly “deja vu” adventure as if he is a game character who respawned in the exact same arena was not an easy adjustment for 24-year-old gamer Tristan Seth Fernandez.

His new encounters inside the campus are a testament now as he embarks on the same journey as it was seven years ago.

From the pursuit of his career in the eSports industry to achieving his dream to become a professor, Tristan’s story is a paragon of resiliency that teaches Josenians how to turn setbacks into opportunities and how to turn those stumbling blocks into stepping stones toward their goals.

The Baffling Dilemma

Reminiscing a certain time frame when he is tested on whether to continue his studies or pursue a career in the eSports industry marked the start of this life-changing dilemma.

At the age of 18, Tristan encountered this formidable challenge that would surely change the course of his destiny, but he tended to surmount it by sacrificing an important part of his life—education over his career.

This decision was heavily influenced by the fact that he’s a late enrollee with an immense school workload to catch up to, even worth mentioning that his chosen program Mass Communication wasn’t aligned with his dream profession to become a professor.

Aside from that, he also shared that his unfortunate financial situation was also the “toughest hindrance” in his school journey.

“Wala ko’y bawn sauna, ambot lang ngano wa ko’y bawn kwarta. Akong klase hantod alas 8 pa sa gabii tas akong money is pang one ride lang sa jeep," he expressed.

Having made a bold decision in the past and considering all influencing factors, Tristan remained committed to hound what he loves doing with no regrets.

Maximizing the Quest for Opportunities

Moving out at such a young age, Tristan somehow found a way to support himself through accepting side jobs.

He made a remarkable name in the eSports industry and accepted notable projects that propelled him to the top.

Tristan worked as a broadcast talent for Mineski and took management roles in companies like RUMBLE ROYALE, AP. Bren, and Cebu’s very own South.gg and even coached Cebuano DOTA teams.

These were the fruits of his labor, an indicator that he was on the right path.

Between 2018 and 2020, he achieved multiple successes, including being the Grand Champion of The Mayor’s Cup 2019, securing the 1st Runner-up position in the Farming Simulator League (FSL) Season 2 qualifiers, and clinching the 2nd Runner-up titles in both the Road to The Nationals Electronic Sports and Gaming Summit (ESGS) and the Acer Predator Cup (APC) 2018.

Tristan viewed this portion of his life as the “sweets of his success.”

Little did they know that there is more to his story than what meets the eye. These attainments were only made possible because of the nights Tristan spent by “sleeping in between jobs.”

Of course, life is not all sweets; it is also about meeting the pressing need to survive a bitter reality. Tristan worked as a barista during the day and a customer representative at night. Life was tough back then for an 18-year-old guy who kept trying to decipher the way out of the labyrinth.

Amidst the pending hardships, he stayed optimistic along the way all in the hope of reaching the finish line. Tristan intensified how much he thrived during those times, yet feeling no amount of exhaustion at all.

“I didn't really feel burnt out or overworked [because] I knew I was working towards something very achievable,” he said.

When one is tested with a tremendous grip of tribulations, their maturity grows, and through these difficulties, they greatly hone their growth as an individual.

Euphoric with achieving more than he expected, he felt that there was still a need for him to go back to his studies.

The Call to U-turn Destination

For anyone who aspires to achieve their aspirations, know that they are valid, even if you encounter setbacks on your path, there’s always a chance to redirect and find purpose moving forward.

Determination is a potent component in this life full of twists and turns, but each challenge that one encounters is an opportunity to learn and grow.

“Whatever I set my mind to, and [if] given a chance to do better this time around, I will,” Fernandez stated.

Being a 24-year-old returnee this academic year brings the “slightest of shame” for him, but this did not deter him from trying again and pursuing his dream of becoming a professor.

“I’m embracing the shamelessness of it. This is me right now. I’m old, and I am getting my life on track,” he added.

In the pursuit of goals, age is never a determining factor.

As long as there is a willingness to strive for better opportunities, growth, and transformation, it remains boundless.

Throughout those experiences, he left a quote that he now instills to motivate him to persevere to finish his education this time.

“On the path towards fulfillment, I am taking the scenic route,” he proudly expressed.

This story is an example that there is no easy way to accomplish goals; there should be obstacles obstructing for us to learn a new lesson, and if ever we make a mistake, at least we come back stronger to break whatever barriers impede us from achieving completion.

“There’s no shame in stepping back; most times it’s how we muster the force to go forward,” Fernandez encouraged.

For anyone who has an ambition and it’s so far away and high up, it’s normal to be tired.

One day you’re gonna look from your feet and you’ll be at your destination.

Tristan Seth Fernandez may be a gamer, but he's now a character in a game of reality, maneuvering the course of his own life.

#OnTheGo

Jaguars outplay Fighting Maroons in Cesafi Men's Volleyball

The University of San Jose-Recoletos (USJ-R) Jaguars claimed victory against the University of the Philippines-Cebu (UPC) Fighting Maroons, 3-0, in the Cesafi 23 Men's Volleyball tournament at the University of Southern Philippines Foundation (USPF) Gymnasium on Saturday, November 4.

The USJ-R Jaguars withstood the persistent rally of the UPC Fighting Maroons with a series of dynamic hits, securing a 25-18 triumph in the first set.

Jaguars' Ehdrienne Suarez and Ed Vincent Flores delivered strong service aces and powerful attacks for the team, including swift dumps.

Despite a few service errors, the Jaguars increased their offensive campaign in the second set and left their opponent with a 12-point lead, 25-13.

The Jaguars also cemented their win over the Fighting Maroons with defensive blocks, finishing a 25-15 in the final set.

Before the match, Jaguars' Coach Roland Potot made the decision to bench the starting six and instead fielded the second team throughout the game, as some of the starting players failed to meet the pre-match training requirements.

“Akong gitan-aw sa ani nga team is to give them a chance as we need the right attitude sa game and practices. Dili lang skill ang atong gitrabaho as a team, also on their character as well,” Potot said.

Meanwhile, Suarez, an open spiker for the Jaguars, shared the team's commitment in their upcoming games.

“In this season, our goal is to keep it low-key this time kay mag-work hard sa mi sa mga lacking sa among team and make more progress pa jud,” he said.

The Jaguars will next face the Cebu Roosevelt Memorial Colleges (CRMC) Mustangs on November 18 at the same venue.

Have you experienced yearning for someone or something you know that will never come back?

For this year’s comeback of FORWARD Publications’ official literary folio, MITNA (Mithi sa Huna-huna), we pine to revisit places and occasions and immerse ourselves once more in the love, joy, sorrow, and regret these particular moments hold.

Josenians, get ready to embark on this journey as we reflect upon cherished memories and lived moments—in print and online!

Coming soon.

#FORWARDMitna2023
